Year = {2024},
Volume = {75},
Pages = {771-795},
Abstract = {A major bottleneck in the crop improvement pipeline is our ability to
   phenotype crops quickly and efficiently. Image-based, high-throughput
   phenotyping has a number of advantages because it is nondestructive and
   reduces human labor, but a new challenge arises in extracting meaningful
   information from large quantities of image data. Deep learning, a type
   of artificial intelligence, is an approach used to analyze image data
   and make predictions on unseen images that ultimately reduces the need
   for human input in computation. Here, we review the basics of deep
   learning, assessments of deep learning success, examples of applications
   of deep learning in plant phenomics, best practices, and open
   challenges.},
